posts.name: Big Bad Breakfast
posts.note: Big Bad Breakfast serves waffles, biscuits, and other hearty daytime eats are served up in a bright, contemporary space. The brainchild of James Beard award-winning chef John Currence, Big Bad Breakfast gives the proper respect to “the most important meal of the day.” Alton Brown recommends the Cathead breakfast, which is a chicken biscuit with crispy fried chicken, cheddar cheese, and sausage gravy. From their website, 'One visit will guarantee you never look at a breakfast plate the same again. Whether it’s the house-cured Tabasco/Brown Sugar Bacon, crispy southern fried chicken, McEwen and Sons grits, or the Anson Mills Steel Cut Oatmeal, you’ll be talking about coming back before you’ve left the table. And don’t forget… we serve lunch too.' NOTE: they have multiple locations.
posts.rcmmnd: Southern Foodways Alliance and Alton Brown

posts.name: Bottega Cafe
posts.note: Bottega Cafe is a relaxed cafe offering fine Italian fare, seasonal specialties, plus wine in a historical setting. Cafe Bottega is Frank and Pardis Stitt’s relaxed spot where you can come for lunch and stay for dinner with a menu celebrating the warm spirit of Italian cuisine while honoring the purest seasonal ingredients of the American South. From their website, ‘Bottega features flavors inspired by the wine bars and trattorias of Italy–from Venice to Palermo. The best aperitifs, wines, beers, cocktails, savory bites, and sublime desserts are offered in a warm and sophisticated atmosphere. Italy inspires the cuisine, carefully crafted by linking ingredients from the American South with artisanal producers from the Italian countryside.’

posts.name: Cafe Dupont
posts.note: Cafe Dupont, around the corner, serves a lovely rabbit gumbo in a white-table-clothed room in a historical building. The chef prepares regional ingredients with a modern Southern spin in a historic, brick-walled bistro. From their website, 'The menu, which changes daily, reflects a fresh perspective on regional ingredients. Classic cooking styles paired with locally grown ingredients create contemporary flavors and signature dishes, such as Fried Oysters & Okra with Cayenne Butter Sauce, Seared Sea Scallops with Goat Cheese Souffle, and Classic Beignets with Home-grown Strawberry Preserves. Café Dupont is a strong supporter of the “slow food” movement, which seeks to encourage the enjoyment of regional produce and traditional foods, which are often grown organically.'

posts.name: El Barrio Restaurante Y Bar
posts.note: El Barrio Restaurante Y Bar is an inventive, sophisticated setting for modern Mexican cuisine and spirits amid bold art and rich woods. Make sure to try their green pozole; it tastes like a Hispanic pho. I read they also make the best salads in town. From their website, 'Multi-regional Mexican-inspired cuisine prepared with seasonally sourced produce, Gulf seafood, and humanely farm-raised meats.'

posts.name: Exotic Wings and Things
posts.note: Exotic Wings and Things is a small place that mostly is carry out for late-night or lunch. Order the lemon-pepper wings, fried okra, and Cajun ranch fries. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Garage Cafe
posts.note: Garage Cafe leads to a wisteria-vined courtyard surrounded by 1930s era parking garages-cum-antique stalls. It is uniquely Birmingham. LIt's a locals' haunt for bustling conversation, beer, and pub grub in a rustic indoor/outdoor setting. It’s also a short stroll down the hill from one of the Southern Foodways Alliance's favorite Birmingham restaurants, Bottega Cafe.

posts.name: Great Wall Chinese Restaurant
posts.note: Great Wall Chinese Restaurant serves Chinese classics, plus Asian fare like hibachi eats and pad Thai, served amid red booths and lanterns. The secret menu at this 30-plus-year old restaurant is the passkey to braised pork belly with smoked mushrooms or the “stir-fried cheese thing” with fermented black beans and chili peppers. From their website, ‘Great Wall Chinese Restaurant is a Chinese cuisine restaurant located in Birmingham, AL. Our menu has a variety of selections for every customer to choose from with reasonable prices. Whether you are looking for the most authentic and tasty Chinese flavored dishes to ignite your tastebuds or something delicate and healthy to satisfy your stomach, China Cafe would always be your wise choice of dining!’

posts.name: Green Acres Cafe
posts.note: Green Acres Cafe serves fried chicken, and fried green tomatoes are served up at this old-school cafe with counter service and founded in 1958 by Charles Gratton. Get a catfish plate slathered with mustard and battered with cornmeal. Order it with the works, and that gets you slathers of ketchup, mustard, and hot sauce on top. From their website, 'Greg Gratton is carrying on a family tradition. In 1958, his father Charles took his life savings and opened the Green Acres Cafe in Birmingham. After decades of success in one location, his father considered investing in a major fast-food chain franchise. But Greg, understanding the value of history and food that Green acres offered, convinced his father to begin his own franchise. After doing all the research and paperwork himself, Greg opened the first Green Acres franchise in 1994. Now, 13 years later, there are 5 locations. The restaurant is well known for their fried chicken wings, pork chops sandwiches, and fried green tomatoes.' NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Gus's Hot Dogs
posts.note: Gus's Hot Dogs is a tiny joint long known for its eclectic hot dog lineup and special sauce, along with burgers and breakfast. While the Birmingham hot dog reminds many of people of their past, it is still a vibrant part of the present fabric of the community. From their website, '“Downtown Birmingham's longest surviving Greek-owned hot dog stand.” Established in 1947, Gus's Hot Dogs proudly serves the Birmingham community with quality, affordable food.'

posts.name: Hero Doughnuts
posts.note: Hero Doughnuts is a brick-and-mortar iteration of a popular pop-up dishing out donuts and burgers until sold out. Owner Wil Drake makes a crazy great apple fritter along with a chicken sandwich that’s as crispy as the fritter. They have fresh, seasonally flavored brioche doughnuts made daily using seasonal and locally sourced ingredients when available — delicious hamburgers on our brioche buns for lunch along with housemade frozen custard. From their website, 'Started from a pop-up. Now we're here. Early mornings, loading a van, setting up a farmer’s market tent in the cold, heat, rain, and sun. The first Hero Doughnuts outpost was a shared commercial kitchen where founder Will Drake’s 2-day process of making brioche-style yeast doughnuts started. Fresh fruit cooked down and mixed into glazes and fillings, topped with crunchy nuts, streusel, chocolate and sprinkles became the expression of joy that customers feel when they taste our doughnuts. What started as a “pop-up” grew into a market stall where folks liked up, and the doughnuts sold out regularly. It became evident that doughnuts matter--they bring people together, spark joy and satisfy our cravings with more than just sugar.' NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: The Lumbar
posts.note: The Lumbar is a new science-themed bar in Pepper Place, situated conveniently near two of our favorite Birmingham restaurants–Chris and Idie Hastings’ Ovenbird with their smoky paella, among other creative and beautifully executed wood-fired menu options; and, Bettola, where we enjoy James Lewis’ Neapolitan-style pizzas, charcuterie, and other seasonal Italian dishes. From their website, 'Good food is brain fuel, and each dish on our menu is specially crafted to feed you and your wildest ideas, whether for a happy hour snack or a late-night bite. You’ll find that most of our dishes feature Hatch green chile, thanks to our founders’ New Mexican roots.'

posts.name: Mac's One Stop
posts.note: Mac's One Stop has been in the Texaco gas station for nearly 30 years. Heather Ehl runs it with her husband Allen, and it's been a family business since 1986. Heather's father, Mack Cribbs, owned a number of gas station and convenience stores in Birmingham. They had a Shell on 5th before purchasing the current location, which was previously an Exxon and turning it into a convenience store. The lunch menu at Mac's has a selection of burgers, sandwiches, chicken, barbecue, and hot dogs.

posts.name: Mom’s Basement
posts.note: Mom’s Basement has a wide selection of beers, some wine, and a few liquors to enjoy while playing board games or pinball machines. It’s located below the small retail center where Tropicaleo serves fantastic Puerto Rican food. From their website, 'Mom’s Basement is a retro-themed dive bar based in Birmingham, Alabama. Fully equipt with alcohol, vintage pinball machines, pool, darts, and a wall covered in cuss words. Bring a picture of your mom to hang on display or just admire the ones already there. Come hang with us at Mom’s.'

posts.name: The Nick
posts.note: The Nick delivers all the dive bar essentials: eclectic jukebox, beer-stained pool tables, and decades of smoke-stained live music handbills plastered on every surface. Although restaurants are theoretically walkable from the Nick, they arrive and depart via rideshare or taxi. The Nick serves cold beer and rock 'n' roll bring hipsters to this bar and music venue for local and big-name acts. From their website, 'We Serve Live Music and Cold Drinks! A “Staple” in Birmingham's Music Scene for over 30 Years. The Nick is 21 and Up Private Club Membership Card ($5 Per Year) and& Valid ID to Enter. The music heard almost every night of the week include local, regional and national acts. The diverse range of acts add to the appeal of an evening at the Nick. One can hear blues, rock, punk, emo, hip-hop, rap, pop, country, metal, bluegrass, rock-a-billy, roots rock, or whatever your genre of choice... The Nick has had it all!'

posts.name: The Ovenbird
posts.note: From their website, 'OvenBird is Chris and Idie Hastings’ live fire, casual restaurant located in Birmingham’s Market District at Pepper Place. Our menu focuses on the amazing seasonal southern ingredients we know and love that takes inspiration from the live-fire traditions of Spain, Portugal, Uruguay, Argentina and, of course, the American South. We have worked closely with some of Alabama's finest craftsmen and leaders in design to create a variety of amazing vignettes for you to enjoy a great meal with your friends, family, or colleagues. We look forward to telling their stories which remind us of how fortunate we are to live in a place like Alabama that celebrates our Southern Makers.' Andrew Zimmern recommends ordering The Boudin Rouge.

posts.name: Post Office Pies
posts.note: Post Office Pies is a stylish outpost for wood-fired pizzas, and local craft beer is located in a historic post office. They started making meatballs that you can get on pies or as an appetizer, and don't forget to order the garlic knots. From their website, 'Post Office Pies is a neighborhood pizzeria that uses fresh ingredients, all locally sourced, house-made dough, and serve local beer and liquor. We are open seven days a week.'

posts.name: Shu Shop
posts.note: Shu Shop is a late-night industry place where chefs go for whiskey. People dig the smoked hamachi collar with yuzu salt: Birmingham's home-grown izakaya and ramen shop.

posts.name: The Standard
posts.note: The Standard serves hamburgers, hot dogs, sandwiches, and fries. In the Pizitz Food Hall, Matt Ralph makes an ideal burger. It’s one of those burgers with crispy edges, served on a potato bun. It’s perfect. The hot dogs and fried bologna sandwiches, I'm told are great too.

posts.name: T-Bones Authentic Philly Style Cheesesteaks and Hoagies
posts.note: T-Bones Authentic Philly Style Cheesesteaks and Hoagies sandwiches are served on genuine Amoroso rolls straight from Philly. The thing that makes us unique is that we are a cheesesteak shop first. Anthony “T-Bone” Crawford griddles cheesesteaks and fries Cajun fries. From their website, 'Our sandwiches are served on genuine Amoroso rolls straight from Philly! The thing that makes us unique is that we are a cheesesteak shop first! People are always hollering about where is the Cheez Whiz, cheesesteaks have been around long before Cheez Whiz. Cheez Whiz is garbage!'

posts.name: Taco Morro Loco
posts.note: Taco Morro Loco has a taco truck and a brick and mortar. They are cranking out the best of the best in authentic Mexican cuisine. Don’t let the service station exterior scare you away because whether it's tacos, salads, homemade salsa, or nachos piled high, the folks at Taco Morro Loco have got you covered. Make sure to order their chorizo burrito or a carnitas taco with buttermilk tomatillo salsa.
